solution:
由题图 1.111，矢量 \(\boldsymbol{r}\) 从 \(\boldsymbol{P}_{1}\) 指向 \(\boldsymbol{P}_{2}\)，把 \(\boldsymbol{P}_{1}\) 产生的电场视为外场，它在 \(P_{2}\) 处的电场强度为

\[
\boldsymbol{E}_{e} = \frac{3\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{r} - r^{2} \boldsymbol{P}_{1}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r^{5}}
\]

因此 \(\boldsymbol{P}_{1}\) 与 \(\boldsymbol{P}_{2}\) 的相互作用力为

\[
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{F} & = \boldsymbol{P}_{2} \cdot \nabla \boldsymbol{E}_{e} \\
& = \frac{3}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r^{7}}\left\{r^{2}\left[\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{P}_{2}\right) \boldsymbol{r} + \left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{P}_{2} + \left(\boldsymbol{P}_{2} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{P}_{1}\right] - 5\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right)\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{2} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{r}\right\}
\end{aligned}
\]

由式(1) 有

\begin{equation*}
\int_{S_{1}} \boldsymbol{E} \cdot \mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{S} = \int_{S_{2}} \boldsymbol{E} \cdot \mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{S} = \frac{\boldsymbol{Q}}{2 \varepsilon_{0}} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

式(2)、式(3)联合，有

$$
\frac{\left(\varepsilon_{0}+\varepsilon\right) K}{2 \varepsilon_{0}} Q = Q
$$

从而得

$$
K = \frac{2 \varepsilon_{0}}{\varepsilon_{0}+\varepsilon}, \quad \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} = \frac{2 \varepsilon_{0} \boldsymbol{E}}{\varepsilon+\varepsilon_{0}}
$$

如题图 1.50，取 $\boldsymbol{E}_0$ 沿 $e_z$ 方向。由于导体可看作介电系数为无穷大的介质，空间的电场为原有均匀静电场以及导体极化电荷激发的电场的叠加，导体球为均匀极化，设极化强度为 $\boldsymbol{P}$，则导体球内外的电场为  

\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{i}} & = \boldsymbol{E}_0 - \frac{1}{3 \varepsilon_0} \boldsymbol{P} \tag{1} \\
\boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{o}} & = \boldsymbol{E}_0 - \frac{4 \pi}{3} a^3 \boldsymbol{P} \cdot \nabla \frac{\boldsymbol{r}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_0 r^3} \tag{2}
\end{align*}

平衡状态下导体内电场为零，故式（1）给出 $\boldsymbol{P} = 3 \varepsilon_0 \boldsymbol{E}_0$。这样得导体球外的电场强度为

\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{o}} & = \boldsymbol{E}_0 - \frac{4 \pi}{3} a^3 \boldsymbol{P} \cdot \nabla \frac{\boldsymbol{r}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_0 r^3} = \boldsymbol{E}_0 - a^3 \boldsymbol{E}_0 \cdot \nabla \frac{\boldsymbol{r}}{r^3} \\
& = \left(1 + \frac{2 a^3}{r^3}\right) E_0 \cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_r - \left(1 - \frac{a^3}{r^3}\right) E_0 \cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_\theta \tag{3}
\end{align*}  

考虑导体球面上的一个小面元，该点处的面电荷密度为  

\begin{equation*}
\sigma = \varepsilon_0 \boldsymbol{e}_r \cdot \left(\boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{o}} - \boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{i}}\right) = 3 \varepsilon_0 E_0 \cos \theta \tag{4}
\end{equation*}

在该面元上面电荷在其附近激发的电场为  

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{o}}' = \frac{\sigma}{2 \varepsilon_0} \boldsymbol{e}_r = \frac{3}{2} E_0 \boldsymbol{e}_r, \quad \boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{i}}' = -\frac{3}{2} E_0 \boldsymbol{e}_r \tag{5}
\end{equation*}  

这样得该面元感受的电场强度为  

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{E} = \left.\boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{o}}\right|_{r = a} - \boldsymbol{E}_{\mathrm{o}}' = -\frac{3}{2} E_0 \boldsymbol{e}_r \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

该面元单位面积所受的电场力为  

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{f} = \sigma \boldsymbol{E} = \frac{9}{2} \varepsilon_0 E_0^2 \cos^2 \theta \boldsymbol{e}_r \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

由对称性，右半球面所受的合力沿 $e_z$ 方向，其大小为  

$$
F_{\mathrm{r}} = \iint \boldsymbol{f} \cdot \boldsymbol{e}_z \,\mathrm{d}s = \frac{9}{2} \varepsilon_0 \pi a^2 E_0^2
$$  

同理可求得左半球面所受的合力大小为 $F_{l} = -\frac{9}{2} \varepsilon_0 \pi a^2 E_0^2$，其中负号代表力沿 $\boldsymbol{e}_z$ 的反方向。

要使电子的速度恒定，必须作用在电子上的合力为零，即

$$
\boldsymbol{F}_{\mathrm{B}}=-\boldsymbol{F}_{\mathrm{E}}=-e E \mathbf{e}_{x}
$$

而 $\boldsymbol{F}_{\mathrm{B}}=-e \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{B}=-e B v \times \mathbf{e}_{z}$，故立刻可知

\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{v}=-\left(\frac{E}{B}\right) \mathbf{e}_{y} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Introduce the magnetic scalar potential $\phi$, where $\boldsymbol{H} = -\nabla \phi$. Since there is no free current in this problem, $\nabla^{2} \phi = 0$, which in cylindrical coordinates becomes

\begin{equation*}
\left\{\frac{1}{r} \cdot \frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r \frac{\partial}{\partial r}\right) + \frac{1}{r^{2}} \cdot \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta^{2}}\right\} \phi = 0 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Due to axial symmetry, $\frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial z^{2}} = 0$. We can set

$$
\phi(r, \theta) = R(r) S(\theta)
$$

yielding

$$
\frac{1}{R}\left(r^{2} \frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} R}{\mathrm{d} r^{2}} + r \frac{\mathrm{d} R}{\mathrm{d} r}\right) = -\frac{1}{S} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} S}{\mathrm{d} \theta^{2}} = m^{2} = \text{constant}
$$

Thus, the general solution of equation (1) is

\begin{equation*}
\phi = \sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(c_{m} r^{m} + d_{m} r^{-m}\right)\left(g_{m} \cos m \theta + h_{m} \sin m \theta\right) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

In this problem, since $\phi(r, \theta) = \phi(r, -\theta)$, the sine terms are not included in equation (2). Divide the space inside and outside the cylinder into three parts as shown in the diagram. The general solution $\phi$ for each part is of the form

\begin{equation*}
\phi_{i} = \sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(c_{i m} r^{m} + d_{i m}\right) \cos m \theta, \quad i=1, 2, 3 \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

For the external region of the cylinder, as $r \rightarrow \infty$, $\phi_{3} = -H_{0} r \cos \theta$, $\mu_{0} H = B_{0}$. From equation (3) we have

$$
c_{31} = -\frac{B_{0}}{\mu_{0}}, \quad c_{3 m} = d_{3 m} = 0, \quad m \neq 1
$$

Hence

\begin{equation*}
\phi_{3} = -\left(\frac{B_{0}}{\mu_{0}} r - \frac{d_{31}}{r}\right) \cos \theta \tag{4}
\end{equation*}

From the boundary conditions at $r = a, b$, we have

\begin{gather*}
\mu_{0} \frac{\partial \phi_{3}}{\partial r} = \left.\mu \frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial r}\right|_{r=a}  \tag{5}\\
\mu_{0} \frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial r} = \left.\mu \frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial r}\right|_{r=b} \\
\frac{\partial \phi_{3}}{\partial \theta} = \left.\frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial \theta}\right|_{r=a}, \quad \frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial \theta} = \left.\frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial \theta}\right|_{r=b} \tag{6}
\end{gather*}

Combining equations (3) and (6), we obtain a system of equations

\[
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
B_{0} + \frac{\mu_{0} d_{31}}{a^{2}} = \mu\left(-c_{21} + \frac{d_{21}}{a^{2}}\right)  \tag{7}\\
-B_{0} + \frac{d_{31}}{a^{2}} = \mu_{0}\left(c_{21} + \frac{d_{21}}{a^{2}}\right) \\
\mu\left(c_{21} - \frac{d_{21}}{b^{2}}\right) = \mu_{0} c_{11} \\
c_{21} + \frac{d_{21}}{b^{2}} = c_{11}
\end{array}\right.
\]

Additionally, since $\phi_{1}$ must be finite at $r = 0$, we have

\begin{equation*}
d_{11} = 0 \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

The magnetic scalar potential inside the cylinder is fully determined by $c_{11}$. Solving equation (7) gives

\begin{equation*}
c_{11} = -\frac{4 \mu a^{2} B_{0}}{a^{2}\left(\mu + \mu_{0}\right)^{2} - \left(\mu - \mu_{0}\right) b^{2}} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

Thus

$$
\phi_{1} = c_{11} r \cos \theta
$$

The magnetic field is

\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{H}_{1} & = -\nabla \phi_{1} = -\frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial r} \boldsymbol{e}_{r} - \frac{1}{r} \cdot \frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial \theta} \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta} \\
& = -c_{11}\left(\cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{r} - \sin \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta}\right) \\
& = -c_{11} \boldsymbol{e}_{z}  \tag{10}\\
& = \frac{4 \mu a^{2}}{a^{2}\left(\mu + \mu_{0}\right)^{2} - \left(\mu - \mu_{0}\right) b^{2}} \boldsymbol{B}_{0}
\end{align*}

When $\mu \gg \mu_{0}$, we have

\begin{equation*}
H_{1} \approx \frac{4}{\mu} \cdot \frac{B_{0}}{1 - \left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^{2}} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}

The larger the $\mu$, the stronger the magnetic shielding effect.

Equation (4) contains an unknown function \(\Lambda(b)\). First, consider its behavior as \(b \rightarrow 0\). According to Gauss's law, the electric field near an infinitely long uniformly charged line is \(E \propto \frac{1}{r}\), where as \(r \rightarrow 0, E \rightarrow \infty\). We expect that the above \(E_{l}\) tends towards \(\infty\) as \(1/b\) when \(b\) approaches 0. For a finite solution, \(\lim_{b \rightarrow 0} \Lambda(b) / b\) should be finite, denoted as \(k\). Substituting this and equation (5) into equation (4), a finite solution can be obtained. Using the method of finding limits, the expression for the charge density \(\sigma_{1}(0, z)\) can be derived as \(\sigma_{1}(0, z)= \frac{\lambda k}{\pi \sqrt{1-z^{2} / f^{2}}} \). Thus, due to rotational symmetry, the surface charge density on the circle is \(\sigma(r)=\left.\sigma_{1}(0, z)\right|_{z=r}\), which gives

\begin{equation*}
\sigma(r)=\frac{\lambda k}{\pi} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\frac{r^{2}}{f^{2}}}}=\frac{\sigma_{0}}{\sqrt{1-\frac{r^{2}}{f^{2}}}} \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

The interaction energy is given by

\[
\begin{align*}
W & = \int \varphi(r) \, \mathrm{d} q = \int \varphi(\boldsymbol{r}) \rho(r) \, \mathrm{d} v \\
& = -\frac{q_{0}^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} a^{3}} \int \frac{1}{r} e^{-\frac{2}{a} r} r^{2} \sin \theta \, \mathrm{d} r \, \mathrm{d} \theta \, \mathrm{d} \phi \tag{2} \\
& = -\frac{q_{0}^{2}}{\varepsilon_{0} a^{3}} \int_{0}^{\infty} r e^{-\frac{2}{a} r} \, \mathrm{d} r = -\frac{q_{0}^{2}}{\varepsilon_{0} a}
\end{align*}
\]

According to Maxwell's equation $\nabla \times \boldsymbol{E} = -\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{B}}{\partial t}$, similar to the solution in part (b), the electric field direction is along the $z$ direction, i.e., $E_{\phi} = 0, E_{\rho} = 0$. For the region $r_1 < r < r_2$, we have

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
E_{z}(r) = E_{0} - \frac{\mu_{0} r^{2}}{4 \pi r_{1}^{2}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d} I}{\mathrm{d} t}, & 0 < r < r_{1} \\
E_{z}(r) = E_{0} - \frac{\mu_{0}}{2 \pi}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\ln \frac{r}{r_{1}}\right) \frac{\mathrm{d} I}{\mathrm{d} t}, & r_{1} < r < r_{2} \\
E_{z}(r) = E_{0} - \frac{\mu_{0}}{2 \pi}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\ln \frac{r_{2}}{r_{1}}\right) \frac{\mathrm{d} I}{\mathrm{d} t}, & r > r_{2}
\end{array}
$$

where $E_{0}$ is the electric field strength in the $z$ direction at $r = 0$.

The work required to move \( q \) to infinity is given by

\[
\begin{aligned}
W & = \int_{a}^{\infty} F \, \mathrm{d} r = \int_{a}^{\infty} \frac{1}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}} \frac{q^{2}}{(2r)^{2}} \, \mathrm{d} r = \frac{q^{2}}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{0} a} \\
& = 0.09 \, \mathrm{J}
\end{aligned}
\]
